{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777081258019,"sessionID":"ses_23db5c505ffejriSGWcGAD1vQd","part":{"id":"prt_dc24c1021001VPWsh8QXUY4iEP","messageID":"msg_dc24bf65e0013Dhh81YBLp7h2v","sessionID":"ses_23db5c505ffejriSGWcGAD1vQd","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777081259102,"sessionID":"ses_23db5c505ffejriSGWcGAD1vQd","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"background_output","callID":"call_h3WZfGGcDKehK4y48q7MQ9iI","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"block":false,"full_session":false,"include_thinking":false,"include_tool_results":false,"message_limit":20,"since_message_id":"","task_id":"bg_26ac2b1d","thinking_max_chars":2000,"timeout":60000},"output":"Task Result\n\nTask ID: bg_26ac2b1d\nDescription: Explore agent-cli schedule mount\nDuration: 56s\nSession ID: ses_23db51d05ffe5V2i2g8oNoSyyx\n\n---\n\nI have inspected the `capability-library\\mycli\\agent-cli` directory and analyzed the `agent-cli.ps1` script. Below is the summary of the `schedule` and `mount` functionality.\n\n### **File & Structure Summary**\n- **`cli.package.json`**: Registry of `mycli` commands including `schedule` and `mount`.\n- **`scripts\\agent-cli.ps1`**: The core logic implementing both features via Windows Task Scheduler.\n- **`state\\schedules\\`**: Stores JSON metadata for one-time scheduled wake-ups.\n- **`state\\mounts\\`**: Stores JSON metadata for persistent \"mounted\" agent lifecycles.\n- **`state\\runs\\`**: Stores run metadata, event logs, and reports for all agent executions (used to determine \"recency\" of work).\n\n---\n\n### **Functionality & Usage**\n\n#### **1. Schedule (One-time Wake-up)**\nSchedules a single, future execution of a prompt for a specific agent.\n- **Commands**: \n  - `mycli agent-cli schedule add --in <delay> --agent <name> --prompt <text> [options]`\n  - `mycli agent-cli schedule list` | `cancel <id>`\n- **Mechanism**: Registers a one-time Windows Scheduled Task. \n- **Use Case**: An agent finishes a sub-task and knows it needs to check back in exactly 1 hour. It calls `schedule add --in 1h` on itself.\n\n#### **2. Mount (Persistent Lifecycle Heartbeat)**\nRegisters a recurring \"heartbeat\" to keep a session alive and ensure progress is monitored.\n- **Commands**:\n  - `mycli agent-cli mount add --agent <name> [--session <id>] [options]`\n  - `mycli agent-cli mount tick <id>` (Manually trigger a heartbeat)\n- **Mechanism**: Registers a recurring Windows Scheduled Task (default 15-minute interval).\n- **Heartbeat Logic**: \n  1. **Skip Check**: Skips the heartbeat if a future `schedule` already exists or if the agent has worked recently (within `quiet_minutes`, default 30).\n  2. **Pulse**: If idle, sends a **Heartbeat Prompt** to the agent.\n  3. **Instruction**: The prompt tells the agent to check context for finished background work or schedule its own next wake-up.\n- **Lifecycle End**: If the agent returns the marker `AGENT_CLI_LIFECYCLE_END`, the mount system notes the lifecycle as finished.\n\n---\n\n### **Context for Analysis Agents (Heartbeat/Wake-up)**\nWhen an agent delegates work (e.g., via `call_omo_agent` in background) and enters a waiting state, it should know:\n\n1.  **Autonomous Wake-up**: The agent can (and should) use `agent-cli schedule add` to set its own \"alarm clock\" based on when it expects background work to finish.\n2.  **Safety Net**: The `mount` system acts as a persistent watchdog. Even if the agent forgets to schedule a wake-up, the mount \"tick\" will eventually wake the session to check for progress.\n3.  **Active Session Awareness**: The system tracks `session_id` and `round`. Agents should resume their specific `session_id` when waking up to maintain state.\n4.  **Quiet Windows**: The mount system respects active work. If an agent is already doing things, the mount won't \"poke\" it with heartbeats.\n\n**Verification**: The logic is fully implemented in `agent-cli.ps1` using native PowerShell `ScheduledTask` cmdlets, ensuring integration with the Windows host environment.\n\n\n\nI have inspected the `agent-cli` project and analyzed the `schedule` and `mount` functionality within `agent-cli.ps1`. \n\n### Summary of Files\n- **`cli.package.json`**: Defines the command registry, mapping `schedule` and `mount` to `scripts\\agent-cli.ps1`.\n- **`scripts\\agent-cli.ps1`**: The core logic implementing both features using Windows Task Scheduler.\n- **`state\\schedules\\`**: Stores JSON records of scheduled wake-ups.\n- **`state\\mounts\\`**: Stores JSON records for persistent agent sessions (\"mounts\").\n- **`state\\runs\\`**: Stores execution metadata, event logs, and final reports used to track agent activity.\n\n### Expected Usage\n\n#### Schedule (`mycli agent-cli schedule`)\nUsed for a **one-time** future wake-up.\n- **Add**: `mycli agent-cli schedule add --in 30m --agent <name> --prompt \"your prompt\"` (or `--at \"2026-04-25 18:30\"`).\n- **Behavior**: Registers a task in Windows Task Scheduler under `\\agent-cli\\`. When triggered, it runs `agent-cli run` with the specified parameters.\n\n#### Mount (`mycli agent-cli mount`)\nUsed for **persistent lifecycle management** through periodic heartbeats.\n- **Add**: `mycli agent-cli mount add --agent <name> --interval_minutes 15`.\n- **Behavior**: Registers a repeating task under `\\agent-cli\\mount\\`. Every interval, it executes a \"tick\".\n- **Heartbeat Logic**: \n  - Skips the tick if a future `schedule` already exists for that session or if there was work within the `quiet_minutes` window.\n  - Otherwise, it sends a lifecycle prompt to the agent.\n  - The agent can end the lifecycle by including `AGENT_CLI_LIFECYCLE_END` in its report, which causes the mount to reset for a fresh session.\n\n### Context for Heartbeat/Wake-up Analysis\nAn analysis agent delegating work should understand the following to implement a \"wake-up\":\n\n1.  **Hand-off**: Before going idle, an agent can call `mycli agent-cli schedule add` to ensure it is woken up at a specific time (e.g., after a long-running external process).\n2.  **Mount Awareness**: If the session is \"mounted,\" the agent will be woken automatically by the heartbeat prompt if it stays quiet longer than the `quiet_minutes` (default 15-30m).\n3.  **The Prompt**: The default heartbeat prompt (lines 2060-2070 in `agent-cli.ps1`) instructs the agent to inspect context, continue work, or schedule its next wake-up.\n4.  **State Tracking**: The `state\\runs\\` metadata (especially `finished_at_utc` and `report_path`) is the source of truth for the `mount` logic to decide if a heartbeat is necessary.","metadata":{"truncated":false,"task_id":"bg_26ac2b1d","agent":"Sisyphus-Junior","category":"quick","description":"Explore agent-cli schedule mount","sessionId":"ses_23db51d05ffe5V2i2g8oNoSyyx"},"title":"quick - Explore agent-cli schedule mount","time":{"start":1777081259088,"end":1777081259101}},"id":"prt_dc24c1022002anVptmOJeHBUdH","sessionID":"ses_23db5c505ffejriSGWcGAD1vQd","messageID":"msg_dc24bf65e0013Dhh81YBLp7h2v"}}
